    <title>Combined summary - Motion to Activate BIP 3</title>
    <updated>2025-11-30T03:02:46.257879+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/CABd6=MPtx9rN2ZtTz7CbT-zb-3qVUecZZrmb56aFyCSVeLxsEQ@mail.gmail.com/T/#mb05e76b1fa6d2e1a2815751ad004fadc3ecf0faf" rel="alternate"/>
    <published>2025-11-05 01:10:00+00:00</published>
    <summary>In a recent exchange on the Bitcoin Development Mailing List, the focus was on refining the process and guidelines for Bitcoin Improvement Proposals (BIPs), specifically concerning the integration of AI and Large Language Models (LLMs) in the drafting of these proposals. A consensus emerged advocating for the reversal of the recently introduced AI rules related to BIP 3, primarily due to the overarching benefits of BIP 3 that surpass the issues associated with LLM-generated content. The discussion underscored the challenge of enforcing a strict prohibition on LLMs, highlighting that such measures could deter beneficial applications of AI while not effectively addressing the core issue of low-quality submissions. It was proposed that expectations be adjusted to empower editors and reviewers to disregard substandard contributions, including those evidently produced by LLMs, thereby maintaining a balance between quality control and the acceptance of AI technologies in content creation.
Melvin Carvalho contributed to the discussion by expressing concerns about the current mechanism for achieving rough consensus within the framework of BIP 3, citing potential conflicts arising from the overlap between authorship and the evaluation of consensus. He referenced RFC 7282, an IETF document on rough consensus, to underscore the importance of avoiding such overlaps. Carvalho suggested a structural safeguard to enhance the legitimacy and fairness of the consensus process: requiring that rough consensus for Process BIPs be confirmed by at least two non-author editors from different implementation ecosystems. This measure aims to distribute responsibility more evenly and protect editors from potential biases when handling contentious proposals.
Additionally, Carvalho pointed out ongoing debates and significant proposed edits to BIP 3, as evidenced by PR 2037. These discussions indicate active disagreements on key aspects of BIP 3's scope and implementation mechanics. This situation highlights the dynamic nature of the discourse surrounding BIP processes and the continuous effort to refine and improve the guidelines to better serve the Bitcoin development community. The dialogue demonstrates a commitment to addressing complex challenges, such as the role of AI in BIP creation, through collaborative discussion and thoughtful consideration of various perspectives within the community.</summary>
